               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18440408-1308-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1308-18440408 t18440408-1308-offence-1 t18440408-1308-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>1308. <persName id="def1-1308-18440408" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1308-18440408" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1308-18440408" type="age" value="30"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1308-18440408" type="surname" value="PURDY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1308-18440408" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOHN PURDY</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18440408-1308-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18440408-1308-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="miscellaneous"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18440408-1308-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="conspiracy"></interp> for a conspiracy.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440408-name-1520" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1520" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1520" type="surname" value="LLOYD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1520" type="given" value="AMELIA CHARLOTE"></interp>AMELIA CHARLOTE LLOYD</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Henry-street, St. George's. On the 11th of Jan. I had a covered cart for sale—Purdy came to me and said he was desired by his master to look for a covered cart of that sort—he thought that would exactly suit him—he would go and bring another gentle-man—he</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184404080230"></xptr>
               <p>said his master was a woollen merchant—he did not say where—I told him the price was 15<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—in about an hour and a half he brought Procter, the pri<lb></lb>soner in the last case—I inquired whether that was the clerk to the woollen mer<lb></lb>chant—he said yes—Procter said his master was out of town—he asked to look at the cart—I showed it him—they examined it—Procter told the prisoner to try it—he asked if he thought it was strong enough—he said yes—they did not bring a horse—he took hold of the two shafts—I borrowed a horse, and they tried the cart—he said it would suit, but his master was out of town, and would not be in town till the Tuesday following, he was a very particular gentleman and liked to do business with the proprietor—he asked if I was the pro<lb></lb>prietor—I said yes—he asked if I would have any objection to take the cart to the gentleman's residence—I agreed to do so when he came in town—he said he would let me know when the gentleman did come—on the Wednes<lb></lb>day Purdy and Procter came again and asked me if I would bring it the following day—I agreed—Purday came at eleven o'clock next morning—he was to take me to the gentleman—he took me to St. Thomas's-street in the Borough—he got out of the cart and brought Procter to me—he began to scold me about detaining him so long, as it was one o'clock—I told him I bad had to run about to borrow the horse—he said "These things will happen in business "—he supposed he must excuse me to his master—he told me to follow him to his master—I turned to do so—he (Procter) said, "If you do not intend to take less than 15<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. you had better ask a little more "—I said I was much obliged—he said, "It will make no difference to me, he bought a horse yesterday that will exactly suit your cart"—I said I would ask 16<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—he took me to his master, John Mellson, he knocked at the door, and Mellson opened it—he began to scold about being detained so long, as be had particular business in the City—he came out, looked at the cart, and asked Purdy if he thought it would suit, he examined the wheel and found some fault with it—I told him I had not brought him a new cart—he asked the price—I said 16<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—he went towards the cart and saw some iron on one of the shafts—he examined it—Purdy said it made it all the stronger—Mellson turned round to Procter and asked if it would suit—he said exceedingly well—I agreed to take 15<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—Procter said to Purdy, "John, you take the cart to the wheeler's"—I turned round to follow Procter to his residence, and left the cart—he said "Have you got a stamp receipt?"—I said, "Sir, I am provided with a receipt"—he said, "This is a common one, it is a sixpenny one "—" But it will do for 20<hi rend="italic">l</hi>" said I—he said, "I want an eighteenpenny one, I will get one"—we knocked at the door—he ordered me to sit down, turned to the servant and told him to go out for something—I suppose for the receipt—I said he was a long time gone—he said, "He will be here presently "—there was a little passage to go down, and I heard him say, "14<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., how foolish"—I said "I will not take less than 15<hi rend="italic">l</hi>."—he said, "I will soon settle that, I will give you 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>."—I said, "Excuse me, but I understood you to say 14<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>."—he gave me a small bit of paper, which was lying on the table, and said, "I will get you to write a receipt for the 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>."—just as I was about to rise he put a bill on the table and said, "I will get you to write on this your name and residence"—I wrote it, and got up, I held my hand out for the money, and he put the bill into my hand—I said, "Sir, I expected the money"—he said, "This is the same as money, read it"—I said, "If I was to read it I don't understand anything about it"—I was very much confused and fright<lb></lb>ened—he said "This is as good as Bank of England money, he had just had a gentleman from the city there who owed him 200<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.," and if I did not under<lb></lb>stand it to pay it away—I came out with my note in my hand—as we were coming out Purdy met us about the spot where I had left the cart—his master</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184404080231"></xptr>
               <p>desired him to see me to the bridge—the cart was gone at that time—I had sold it for money—I had no intention to take a bill whatever—I saw no more of them—I have been searching for them ever since—I traced my cart to Mr. Dowsett's—it was sold, I understand.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. HORRY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You were to agree to give some<lb></lb>thing to Purdy? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, at the time this was going on about the bill he was not present—when it was over he was coming up—he came and asked me if it was to sell—throughout the whole he appeared to be acting under the direction of Procter and Mellson.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> The contract was made before you want into the house, and you thought it was for ready money? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440408-name-1521" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1521" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1521" type="surname" value="DICKENS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1521" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>MART DICKENS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am single and lire with my brother John in St. Tho<lb></lb>mas's-street. On the 10th of January I had a bill in my window for lodgings—Mellson and another man cane and took a bed-room, and asked for the use of a parlour—they told me they were engaged in the City the whole of the day, till about five o'clock in the evening—I do not know who the other man was—I have not seen him since—H was not Purdy—they came on Friday evening, and said, they had a letter requesting their immediate attendance in the country as a relation bad died and left them some money, they must go off by the first train, and would be there the following night—he did not return to pay me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Was not the person that came with Mellson the per<lb></lb>son that you have since seen at Procter? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I have not seen him—I did not tee him before the Magistrate.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440408-name-1522" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1522" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1522" type="surname" value="HOBMAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1522" type="given" value="CHRISTOPHER"></interp>CHRISTOPHER HOBMAN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a horse-dealer, and live in John-street Har<lb></lb>per-street, New Kent-road. On the 12th of January, about four o'clock in the afternoon, there was a cart in the street opposite my door—Mellson was with it—I have seen him before at fairs and markets—fee called on me, and asked if I would change with him for a lighter one—I said I could not—I bought it for 16<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I do not know Procter at all—I sent it down to Mr. Dowsett's yard—I left word there that I had such a thing to part with—Mrs. Lloyd's foreman, Joseph Buck came and saw it—I did not know Mellton a a wool<lb></lb>len-draper—I think I should have known if he had been so—I alway con<lb></lb>sidered him to be dabbling about telling horses—I never saw any woollen goods with him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440408-name-1523" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1523" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1523" type="surname" value="DOWSETT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1523" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN DOWSETT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a wheelwright. On Saturday morning, the 11th or 12th of January, Mr. Hobman brought the cart to me—Mrs. Lloyd's fore-man came and identified it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440408-name-1524" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1524" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1524" type="surname" value="TEAKLE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1524" type="given" value="GEOROI"></interp>GEOROI TEAKLE</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-sergeant H</hi> 8.) On the 26th of Jan, Purdy. came to me, by appointment, on another charge not connected with this—I said I wanted him about a cart—he said, "What I did was on commission" I said, "I have no alternative but to take you before the Magistrate—he said, "I received 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. in the pound, 13<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. wat all that I had"—I know Mellson; but not as a woollen-merchant—I always considered him as a horse-dealer—I have seen him at Smithfield-market, and at fairs, in company with horse<lb></lb>dealers.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> I believe you called at hit lodging the night before and and saw his wife? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> She spoke to me—he asked me to let him go, and he would come to the office—I did not do to.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18440408-name-1525" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18440408-name-1525" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
